			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><a href="http://www.therunes.net/forums/viewtopic.php?t=4837" target="_blank">http://www.therunes.net/forums/viewtopic.php?t=4837</a>
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">What process did you use for redesigning this zone, what new features 
<br />
can we expect, and when do you think this will go live?</span>
<br />

<br />
I basically started from the ground up when redesigning the zone: I 
<br />
re-pathed the zone, took the pre-existing NPCs that were in the zone and 
<br />
removed them, added in new NPCs, new items, new quests, and texts in 
<br />
general for all the creatures in the zone. Other than what the dragons 
<br />
are named, what the creatures looked like, and the geometry of the zone, 
<br />
everything else in Veeshan's Peak is new, while still retaining that 
<br />
familiar look and feel. 
<br />

<br />
One new feature that you will see in Veeshan's Peak is the first 
<br />
introduction of item-based recast timers. Before, items that had 
<br />
clicky-spells on them were made with the thought to make the cast time 
<br />
on the item extremely long to balance it. Of course, mod-rods and the 
<br />
Donal's Breastplate had a recast timer, but those were special 
<br />
circumstances where we used special-case code to allow those items to 
<br />
function the way they do. With item recast timers, however, we can now 
<br />
make items that have a relatively fast cast time, and balance it around 
<br />
the fact that you cannot use the item more than once in a specific 
<br />
amount of time. Item recast timers are a great thing, and will help make 
<br />
items more varied in the future. 
<br />

<br />
The zone went Live on Wednesday July 14th. Go play there now! 
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Camille, what was your theme inspiration for redesigning such a well 
<br />
loved zone as Veeshan's Peak?</span> 
<br />

<br />
I had a lot of great experiences, and some not so great experiences, 
<br />
with Veeshan's Peak raiding it in Kunark. In the current EverQuest, 
<br />
Veeshan's Peak was extremely underused, and many players skipped 
<br />
Veeshan's Peak all-together. My main inspiration was to make this zone 
<br />
more visited than it currently was, while trying to fix some of the 'not 
<br />
so great' experiences I had with it. Hopefully I've accomplished that. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Into the facts, what level range, gear, and experience are we 
<br />
looking at to be able to adventure here, will it be more of a group 
<br />
exploration or raid zone? </span>
<br />

<br />
I tried to make the new Veeshan's Peak a little of everything. The 
<br />
dragons give quests to you if you're allied to their faction, you can 
<br />
experience group in the zone if you don't care for questing, and you can 
<br />
also raid the dragons for some gear. The zone is intended to be a 
<br />
playground for both casual and power gamer, with the key quest being 
<br />
accessible to both. The final encounter to gain access into Veeshan's 
<br />
Peak already has been defeated by pickup raids, so I have no doubt 
<br />
everyone will get a chance to experience the zone. 
<br />

<br />
The level range of the zone is level 65s, with pre-elemental to 
<br />
elemental level gear for the raids, primarily. The raids drop elemental 
<br />
planes quality raid loot, while the experience group portions drop 
<br />
sub-elemental level drops. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Quests, Quests, and more Quests! Tell us a little about how you 
<br />
implemented these, and the different sides that we may take. </span>
<br />

<br />
Basically, you pick a side and stay with it. If you choose to not kill 
<br />
the dragons, or any of their followers, you can do quests in the zone to 
<br />
get some good quality rewards. I've made it so that flip-flopping 
<br />
factions to do both the quests and hunt in the zone to be very painful, 
<br />
with all of the NPCs in Veeshan's Peak getting very angry at you after 
<br />
only a few kills. Each dragon has 1 quest that they offer, and each 
<br />
dragon has both a melee/hybrid reward and a caster/priest reward. 
<br />

<br />
The quests entail you traveling all over Norrath, and even Luclin and 
<br />
the Planes, for various things. You could be out to avenge a fallen 
<br />
dragon's death, or you could be doing something as simple as delivering 
<br />
notes to other dragons, or collecting items to make a dragon a new spell 
<br />
for them to use. I hope everyone enjoys figuring out these quests. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Dragons, oh my! We miss these, I personally think thats why people 
<br />
have such high expectations for VP, will we be seeing familiar 
<br />
characters? </span>
<br />

<br />
Yes, all of the old dragons are still there, along with a few new 
<br />
friends and followers. Some of these new followers are combatable, while 
<br />
others are there for flavor. Dry Sapara, one of the new followers in 
<br />
Skyfire Mountains is the new gate keeper to Veeshan's Peak though he 
<br />
seems to do a bad job of keeping players out J. Most of the old dragons 
<br />
have similar abilities to the pre-revamped zone, though some of them 
<br />
have picked up new tricks. I wanted to make sure I kept the "feel" of 
<br />
the original encounters in tact. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">What process did you use for redesigning this zone, what new 
<br />
features can we expect, and when do you think this will go live? </span>
<br />

<br />
I basically started from the ground up when redesigning the zone: I 
<br />
re-pathed the zone, took the pre-existing NPCs that were in the zone and 
<br />
removed them, added in new NPCs, new items, new quests, and texts in 
<br />
general for all the creatures in the zone. Other than what the dragons 
<br />
are named, what the creatures looked like, and the geometry of the zone, 
<br />
everything else in Veeshan's Peakis new, while still retaining that 
<br />
familiar look and feel. 
<br />

<br />
The zone went Live on Wednesday July 14th. Go play there now! 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Final question, if you could tell us one thing, be it the most 
<br />
innovative, or challenging part of the revamp, or just your favorite 
<br />
part of the old zone that youve preserved, what is it? </span>
<br />

<br />
The most innovative thing I did was to give those darn globes in Skyfire 
<br />
a purpose! Before, there were speculations on what they did, what the 
<br />
intent of the globes were, as well as some funny rumors like clicking 
<br />
them in a specific order (or all at once) spawned Veeshan, or created a 
<br />
portal to Veeshan's lair. 
<br />

<br />
The most challenging part of the revamp was getting a better 
<br />
understanding of scripting. My knowledge of scripting was limited until 
<br />
I started my work on Veeshan's Peak, and after bugging the heck out of 
<br />
Prathun, Maddoc, Lyndro, as well as a few others, (thanks guys!) I feel 
<br />
pretty confident about my scripting and ability to make NPCs do some 
<br />
wacky things. 
<br />

<br />
My favorite part of the old zone that I preserved, no question, was the 
<br />
dragons! I mean, imagine a Veeshan's Peak with something other than 
<br />
dragons. I'm thinking 30 foot tall snow bunnies wouldn't be fun to 
<br />
kill...well, on second thought they might be, hehe. But without a doubt, 
<br />
I'd say it's the dragons.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
